article.description: Steve Francis scored 22 of his 30 points after halftime, including the final 14 points for the Houston Rockets, who rallied for an 86-83 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers.
article.headline: Francis scores Rockets' final 16 points
article.linkText: Francis takes command, single-handedly snuffs Blazers
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- A painful third-quarter fall couldn't stop Steve Francis.
Francis

Francis got up slowly from the spill but was going strong by the fourth quarter as he scored Houston's final 16 points and led the Rockets over the Portland Trail Blazers 86-83 Tuesday night. "It was over exaggerated,'' Francis said. "I got up. As long as I get up, I'm OK. It's just something that happened.'' Francis, who scored 18 of his 30 points in the fourth quarter, made a layup with 20 seconds left to put the Rockets ahead to stay at 85-83 and closed it out with a free throw. Rasheed Wallace's 3-pointer with 3.3 seconds to play missed the mark and Eddie Griffin rebounded for the Rockets, ending the game. Francis fell hard under Houston's basket with 4:43 left in the third quarter following a flagrant foul from Wallace. Francis remained in the game but took heat treatments on his lower back during each timeout. "He's a warrior, there was no doubt in my mind if he could walk, he was going to play,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "He had those headaches all last year and fought through them. He's a tough guy.'' Francis missed playing time last season with migraine-like headaches that have since been cured. "Francis took over the game late and I thought we had good defense on him,'' Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said. "When he's making his jump shot he's tough to stop. We didn't win the game because of the third quarter. "We did some good things but not quite enough of them.'' With Francis carrying the offensive burden, the Rockets picked up their defensive pace to get the victory. "Our defense won it,'' Cuttino Mobley said. "You have to play defense. Everyone knows I can score 22 points, but I have to show them I can play defense.'' Yao Ming played 15 minutes for the Rockets and scored seven points with four rebounds, two assists and a blocked shot. Griffin had 14 points and Kenny Thomas added 12 for the Rockets. Portland had four players with 12 points each: Bonzi Wells, Dale Davis, Scottie Pippen and Arvydas Sabonis. "We didn't shoot the ball well in the second half,'' Pippen said. "We tried to attack them in the zone.'' Houston started slowly, falling behind 27-13, and trailed 58-48 at halftime before pulling even at 76 on Francis' 18-foot jumper with 5:41 to play. He put them in the lead moments later, slamming home an alley-oop pass from Cuttino Mobley with 5:12 left. "When he dunked that one, it was crazy after that,'' Mobley said. "We kind of took off and the momentum went our way.'' Maurice Taylor played in his first game in more than a year. He missed last season recovering from Achilles' tendon surgery and he was suspended the first five games this season for violating the league's drug policy. "It's great to have him back,'' Tomjanovich said. "He made some big plays for us. It just takes time to get that playing shape.''

Game notes
Rockets starting C Kelvin Cato missed the game to attend the funeral of his grandmother. Moochie Norris wore armbands with Cato's jersey number, 13 ... Pippen, who played for the Rockets in 1998-99, is still roundly booed when he returns to Compaq Center. "They still love me here,'' Pippen said, smiling. "It doesn't bother me. I'm used to playing in hostile environments. It doesn't distract me.''
